    Archives and Silences: Writing African History: Archival records, especially written documents are often assumed to be the authoritative sources for documenting historical events. Nevertheless, historians have questioned this assumption, shedding light on how archival records not only perpetuate omissions and inequalities but also advocate for using sources like oral traditions and rumors to reconstruct the past. With African history as its case study, this course invites students to explore the methodologies employed by historians in crafting narratives on topics such as gender, slavery, animal-human relations, and urbanization. Emphasizing diverse sources like songs, fiction, photography, the built environment, and surveys, students will discover how scholars amplify marginalized voices in historical narratives.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
We will aim to tackle questions such as: How were archival records and institutions that preserve them created? How do historians navigate archival formation and silences in their research and writing? Which new innovative sources have historians incorporated beyond official records? What are the possibilities and limitations of their methodological approaches?
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Course activities will include conducting oral interviews, critiquing museum exhibitions, and writing research papers that account for issues of power and inequality in archives and in the field of African history. After taking this course, students will be able to assess and apply historical methodology tools in their respective fields of study.

    This course will examine the nexus between the humanitarian crisis in Africa and the media through a case study format. It will explore the media-humanitarian relationship in four periods: the period immediately after independence in the 1960s, the Cold War, which lasted until the late 1980s, during the multiparty period, and the War on Terror, which started after September 11.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The course will also explore the changing humanitarian landscape from its early bootstrapped days in Biafra when it was purely driven by charitable instinct to its present professionalized project. Likewise, the media landscape has witnessed a radical shift; the newspaper was the primary media, especially photos, during the Biafra conflict. Ethiopia&#39;s 1984/5 famine was TV&#39;s moment, but in Ethiopia in 2020, social media was the principal site of engagement.

    Environmental anthropology has historically asked questions about how humans relate to the interconnected biophysical and cultural processes unfolding in the locales where they live. From Franz Boas&rsquo;s reflections on geography and cultural diffusion, Bronislaw Malinowski&rsquo;s study of gardens and magic, and E. E. Evans-Prichard&rsquo;s explorations of pastoralism and economy to Julian Steward&rsquo;s analysis of cultural ecology and tradition, environmental anthropology has always encompassed a broad range of thinkers and conceptual tools. Less often acknowledged, however, is that this perspective has not always been applied in a way that explicitly reflects on how we cite or integrate new scholarship into the field.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
This course explores processes of power and expertise and the way they work relationally to shape people&rsquo;s claims to the environment. It strives to continue environmental anthropology&rsquo;s movement beyond problematic imaginaries of nature as foundational, beyond a reifying focus on subalterity, beyond unproblematized images of marginalization, and beyond the uncritical use of the savage slot. Furthermore, this project is not concerned with listing people who are the most recognizable. Instead, it promotes critical intersectionality within environmental anthropology, articulating a political stance from which to rethink environments.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Intersectional Ecologies takes the field in a new direction. This course builds on scholarship that expands debates about the value of anthropology to the humanistic study of the environment. These themes are guideposts for thinking about the environment in its many dimensions. This course attempts to offer theoretical and regional breadth that pushes at the intellectual and practical boundaries of environmental anthropology.

    The emergence of the &ldquo;Arab Regional System&rdquo; in 1945 coincided with the onset of the nuclear age. Three years later, Israel was established and the first Arab-Israeli war broke out. Since the very inception of the conflict, the arms race in general and the quest for a nuclear bomb in particular came to the forefront of the war and escalation dynamics between Israel from one side and key Arab actors from the other side. The nuclear bomb has been a dominant factor in the security discourse in the Arab world. The latter found itself surrounded by a nuclear periphery, namely a nuclear-armed Israel; a nuclear-capable Iran, and a nuclear-aspirant Turkey with tactical nuclear weapons positioned on its territories. Such a trilogy has been instrumental in investigating different schools of thought about the security dilemma in the region.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Within this context, this course addresses the nuclear age in the Arab world in relation to Israel&rsquo;s nuclear monopoly and the overlapping relations with Iran and Turkey. In so doing, it investigates the nuclear decisions of Egypt, Syria and Iraq. Moreover, it tackles the resurgent debate about the &ldquo;nuclear awakening&rdquo; in the Middle East, particularly in reference to the prospect of the Saudi nuclear ambition. Throughout the course, each case is addressed within the context of underscoring the continuity and change in the nuclear discourse, namely the centrality of Israel&rsquo;s nuclear posture compared to Iran&rsquo;s and Turkey&rsquo;s nascent nuclear ambitions.

    How do we understand the Arab Middle East and North Africa? The first part of the course looks at how the Arab world itself has sought to answer this question, from the cultural revival of the Nahda to the radical nationalisms of the 20th century to 21st-century identity politics. The second part of the course looks at the politics of knowledge: what concepts, approaches, and paradigms have scholars in the West used to study the region - and how does scholarship relate to contemporary geopolitics? Finally, we explore representations of the Middle East in popular culture, including tv, film, novels, and video games. 
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Introduction to Arab Studies&#39; will be of interest to students taking the undergraduate Certificate in Arab Studies (who will complete their capstone thesis during the course) as well as those majoring in Regional and Comparative Studies with the Middle East and North Africa focus.

    This course is intended to introduce students to the politics of the Middle East by exploring some of the main political and social problems facing the region today. The topics covered emerge from academic, policy, and everyday debates about real-world questions and challenges that have affected and continue to affect the lives of people in the Middle East. We will debate these questions ourselves, and scrutinize how they have been studied and analyzed by scholars who work on the region. We will also dwell on more fundamental questions of how research agendas emerge, which questions end up being studied and why, and the relationship between area studies knowledge and general theories of comparative politics.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Each week we will read four important works that each in their own way seek to make sense of a set of puzzles or questions related to that week&rsquo;s topic. These works include a mix of &lsquo;classic&rsquo; texts in the field of Middle East comparative politics and newer research on the same questions. We will also, where possible, integrate other types of media, like memoirs, novels, and films. The focus of the course is on the 20th and 21st centuries, though occasionally we may discuss more historical periods.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The course is structured as a survey and, as such, we will be aiming to cover a broad range of topics, including state formation, authoritarianism, oil and rentierism, political Islam, conflict, sectarianism, and the Arab Spring revolutions. The topics we will cover are certainly not exhaustive, but they are selected to capture some of the most significant debates and questions that have motivated research on the region. Students will have the opportunity in their final assignments to delve more deeply into one of these topics, or to explore one that we haven&rsquo;t covered in the course.

    The purpose of this seminar is to help participants understand the power of Congress in the development of America&rsquo;s Asia policy. It will focus on a series of case studies since the end of the Cold War, among them, Burma policy, normalization of relations with Vietnam, China&rsquo;s WTO accession, the US-India civil nuclear agreement, Taiwan arms sales, Hong Kong policy, TPP, US-China mil-mil relations, North Korea sanctions, CFIUS Reform, and AUMF/War Powers. Drawing on the Congressional Record and hearing transcripts, as well contemporary accounts of the policy debates in the media, the course will examine the political dynamics, Congressional procedures, personalities, constituencies, executive branch perspectives and foreign policy environments at play in each case. It will also incorporate discussions with practitioners.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
The course will be open to graduate students and will meet once weekly for approximately two-and-a-half hours. Class will consist of minimal lecture. It will require students to study and internalize the perspectives of key figures and/or institutions in the debates for purposes of class discussion. Based on the discussions, each student will draft two page memo advising a Senator on how to vote in each of six case studies. There will be a take-home final examination.

    This seminar examines the international political economy of Asia. The region is undoubtedly of critical importance: it is home to half the world&#39;s population, and rapid economic development has fueled global economic growth. Yet it is also a region experiencing political and social changes that have profound implications for regional and global stability. This seminar analyzes trends in the region by examining the political nature of the most salient economic issues and their implications for policy and private sectors.
&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Students are not expected to have an advanced proficiency in economics; however, it is highly recommended that students have some background in basic macroeconomic concepts and a certain familiarity with the international monetary and trading system.

